	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Astroshak</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Senior Member<br />
	
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jan 2002<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Talyandrei Thistleshade</b><br /><i>You act as if somehow the rich earned what they have. </i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>The rich who pay income taxes are working and earning their way.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />The poor and middle income do most of the work and create most of the innovation. The rich just make the profit off of it. Most of the wealth held in western world has been acquired through the exploitation of others.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>If you choose to regard paying someone to do a job as exploitation, I cannot argue with this.  And there were indeed company towns, where the company owned everything.  And there are sweatshops.  However, assuming that these situations are the norm is absurd.  In today's economy, with all the jobs being created, we are fast approaching the time, once again, where there is a surplus of jobs and a defecit of bodies to fill them.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Anyway, now the rich are NOT paying their share, the middle income earners are footing the bill for the excesses of the wealthy. Gotta love this Patrician-Plebian arrangement.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>If you believe that the rich are required somehow, by virtue of owning more wealth, to pay a larger percentage of their wealth in taxes, more power to you.  However, it is silly to assume that because someone is making 10k more than someone else, per year, that he has to pay a higher percentage in taxes.  Progressive taxes simply punish the rich for daring to make more money than anyone else, which is little more than a communist sentiment.<br />
 <br />
Kanin, please show me where you got the idea that it is normal for the rich to use people like beasts of burden.  I'd love to be enlightened about this.  Because I can honestly say that I have seen isolated incidents (sweatshops, for example) but nothing that has indicated it was the norm. <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>KaninZ</b><br /><i>The acquisition of wealth is an illussionary approach to life when the emphasis should be on the betterment of yourself and mankind</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Interesting quote; too bad that it is generally the acquisition of said wealth that provides one with the chance to better him/herself.   Also considering that the individual is a part of society, and thus bettering him/herself is therefore also bettering society.  <br />
 <br />
Socialism is the idea that everyone pays for everyone else.  Not too far from communism; in fact it is a stage of society between capitalism and communism (<a href="http://www.m-w.com/cgi-bin/dictionary?book=Dictionary&amp;va=socialism" target="_blank">http://www.m-w.com/cgi-bin/dictiona...ry&amp;va=socialism</a>).  The basic idea being that if someone is "needy", then it is not that person's fault, but society's.  However, simply because someone is "needy" does not obligate anyone else to help that "needy" person out.  Most everyone would agree that it is generous to help the "needy" person out; but it is NOT a requirement.  To assume that it is a requirement simply places the collar of slavery around your neck, with the "needy" holding the other end of the leash.  <br />
 <br />
Jesus Christ, people!  Stop assuming that the top 1 percent income people are the ones keeping you down WHEN IT IS THE ATTITUDES INHERENT IN SOCIALISM/COMMUNISM KEEPING YOU DOWN!!!!!</p>
	
	
	
