	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>AegnorCuthalion</b><br /><i>So you are saying that the top 2% should pay 90% of the taxes.  That is just insane.  Of course it would end up bankrupting the U.S. if it did occur.  The loss of revenue from such a policy would be staggering.  The government is MUCH less effecient with money, so the loss of that much money from the economy would frankly cause a depression the likes of which we haven't seen since the 30's.<br />
 </i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>If they make 90% of the money, then yes, they SHOULD pay 90% of the taxes. You know why nobody is ever going to implement the "flat tax" that the right wing pretends to want so badly? Because it would increase what the rich pay. If everybody payed the same percentage of their income, that top 2% would pay their 90% of the taxes, as they make 90% of the money. I don't think you've done the math in your head:<br />
<br />
To model our economy:<br />
<br />
out of 100 people that made a total of $1000 between them all, and paid a total of $200 in taxes:<br />
<br />
2 of those 100 people made $900 between them. They only paid about $160 in taxes (80% of the tax burden) between them, pocketing the remaining $740 dollars.<br />
<br />
98 of the rest split the remaining $100. Out of that $100, they paid $40, so they really only had $60 to split between them.<br />
<br />
Do you really think those 2 people paid their fair share? In a flat tax system, at the same tax rate, everyone would pay 20% so those top two would have paid $180 in taxes (90% of the tax burden), the other 98 people would have paid $20 in taxes.</p>
	
	
	
