	<!-- message -->
	<p>EDITED to separate what was directed at Taly from the rest of my post directed at this conversation in general.<br />
 <br />
 <br />
 <br />
Taly, you <i>really</i> need to make a distinction between wealth by inheritance and wealth by working smart. To paraphrase something you said in an earlier post, you act as if somehow coming from a poor family and taking advantage of the opportunities available in this society to become rich means you didn't earn it and don't deserve it.<br />
<br />
------------------------------------------------------<br />
<br />
Regarding this topic:<br />
<br />
It's been my experience that the people who hate the wealthy and who talk about things like spiritual enlightenment being more important are generally the ones who aren't wealthy and who don't see themselves ever being wealthy. It's a defense mechanism that they use to justify being poor.<br />
<br />
Money is not good, money is not evil. Money is a neutral tool. What you do with it is good or evil.<br />
<br />
Social ills that you want to cure? Become wealthy and throw money at the problem. Don't think you can become wealthy? That's your problem. Don't try to make it someone else's by attempting to take what you perceive as the higher ground and belittling people who have a dream bigger than yours and the will to reach for it.<br />
<br />
<br />
Here's a clue for you. I'd rather be wealthy and spiritually enlightened than be poor and spiritually enlightened. Cash gives you the opportunity to spread that enlightenment.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />Tevyn Eagleye<br />
51st Pathfinder of Solusek Ro<br />
Retired</div>
	
