	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />What if we reach a point where there's a small percentage of people making hundreds of millions a year, or billions, and a larger number of people making minimum wage. Would that be fair ? And I surely hope you don't believe that could never happen.<hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br />
I am saying that I do not believe that that will happen (that is what happens to the economy of dictitorial regemes btw).  In the system we have, the gap between the rich an the poor may very well get bigger.  But which is better...<br />
(Some make belive place...ie numbers are made up)<br />
A) Poor make $100 a year, rich make $200 a year.  Poor cannot afford a TV, they make do with a radio.  They can't afford a car.<br />
The rich can afford a black and white TV, and can usually afford a car.<br />
or<br />
B) Poor make $500 a year, the rich make $10000.  The poor can afford multiple color TVs, and usually more then one car per household.<br />
The rich can affort yachts and limos, and private jets.<br />
 <br />
Which society would you rather live in?  My point is that the so called "gap" between the rich and the poor is meaningless.  What is meaningful is the standard of living of a people.<br />
 <br />
You are locked into thinking of wealth as some sort of fixed sized pie.  So if someone is rich and get a bigger peice of pie, that means that someone else is getting less.  That is simply not true.  What is really happening is they are baking a new pie...and society gets a big portion of it.  Not just through taxes, but also through investment which creates jobs, and also through buying things such as cars, which result in raises for those building the cars.</p>
	
	
	
