<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Jeryn</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Senior Member<br />
	
	
	<br />
	Joined: May 2000<br />
	Location: Knoxville, TN  USA
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Wouldn't it be nice if tax burden really was just as simple as who pays in what? Unfortunately, it's a little more complex than that, because that tax burden is going to pay for things. It goes to service debt, it goes to prop up social security, to a defense budget, to education, etc.<br />
<br />
Just for an example, my fiance and I are comfortable, we're not rich by any stretch of the imagination, but we're comfortable. Consider for a sec that some of the money we pay in taxes goes to education. My fiance has a five year old boy, and after I finish up the degree I'm working on right now, we want to have another child -- maybe two more if I can talk her into it <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /> (She's told me that a third kid is fine so long as I carry it, though, so I think that's an uphill battle for me. Anyway!...) He's going to Montessori school, and has been since he's three, because we (and his dad, too) believe he's getting a better education there than he would at the public school he's zoned for. So we're paying whatever portion of our taxes go to schools, and then we're paying -- and that paying feels pretty heavy come tuition time -- for him to go to school on top of those taxes for schools we don't even use.<br />
<br />
When people with a majority of the wealth are paying a majority of the tax burden, they're paying for programs and services that in some instances they're never going to utilize themselves. If we're going to get into trying to arrive at what's equitable, let's try to look at both sides of the coin <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /></p>
	
	
	
