<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Astroshak</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Senior Member<br />
	
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jan 2002<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>AegnorCuthalion</b><br /><i><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />It is impossible to get rich through a win-win system if the transaction is closed, i.e. if you and I are the only two affected by the trade.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Sheesh...what B.S.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br />
Actually, this is entirely correct.  In a zero-sum situation, the only way to come out ahead is if the other guy comes out behind.  However, what this completely ignores is that the economy, whether you're talking a personal, local, or countrywide economy, is NOT a zero sum situation.  Otherwise, the economy could never have grown.<br />
 <br />
Here's an example.  I come up with a new product.  The cost of the raw materials to manufacture this product is $2.00 per piece.  The cost of the labor, and the fixed expenses (rent, electricity, taxes, etc) are relevant to a real world situation, such as making the product in a factory, but lets set those aside for now.  I turn around and sell that product for $20.00.  Thats $18.00 profit (again, in Real Life, thats not $18 profit, thats $18 minus the cost of labor, minus the fixed expenses, to find out how much is actual profit).  In short, I took $2 worth of material, and turned it into a $20 product.  This would be impossible in a zero sum situation; the value of the finished product would also have to be $2 in a zero sum game.<br />
 <br />
Those who believe that wealth in this country should be distributed evenly regardless of personal contribution (those who rail against the rich being rich, just because they are rich) would consider a $20 price tag crazy, $18 profit obscene.  Yet if people are willing to buy the product at $20, then the price is considered by those people to be fair and equitable.  Trying to price it at $40 might find nearly as many people interested nin it, or might find almost no one interested in it.  Thats part of supply and demand.  <br />
 <br />
Does supply and demand take advantage of people?  While its fluctuating, sure.  People often buy games right when they come out, paying a premium on having it first.   Later, as demand drops, so does the price, so those who waited pay less.  Were those who paid more, buying the game when it first came out, were they burned?  Often they'll tell you they were happy to have gotten it, or else they'll tell you the game was a waste of money, depending on whether they liked the game, irregardless of how much they actually paid for it.<br />
 <br />
BTW, Taly, I've said before that the right won't go for a flat tax any more than the left would.  The right won't go for it because then taxes won't be so high on the rich, and they would be unable to offer tax breaks to the rich.  That, IMO, is the biggest reason the right won't go for it.  Even though it would reduce, not raise, the tax burden of the rich.  It is a mathematical impossibility for it to raise the tax burden on the rich, when 50 percent of the US does not pay taxes, and many of that 50 percent gets money back from the government in the form of credits, meaning that their net sum of paid taxes is in the negative, not the positive or zero.  The left won't go for a flat tax because that would mean those people making money off of the government would actually have to pay taxes, and woiuld be taken off the government's dole.  The left needs people on the dole, because keeping them there is how the left gets its power base.</p>
	
	
	
